and had earned the book, or something to that effect. If he fought and bled 57 times, and a random pally shows up to his 1 and only fear raid he ever plans on attending and wins a pally item, that isn't at all fair to the blood the older pally has shed not just in the name of the CoG, but in the name of EVERYONE else who has EVER won anything on a CoG raid that pally attended. Does he deserve it more than other people? Maybe. Does he deserve it more than the new pally? Yes, yes he does. And any of you who have won a roll on your own item while the older pally was there should be cheering for him to win something as well; anything else is not only unjust, it's selfish.<br><br><br>&gt;it makes people who just reached level 46/47 and are new<br>&gt;to the planes feel less appreciated than others <br><br>I completely disagree with you here. Last night was my first fear raid, and I was 46. Did I win a lotto on the only druid drop? No, I lost to someone with a significant bonus advantage. But I didn't go to the raid for lewt (though that would be a nice fringe-benefit if it had happened). I went to meet some new people, to see a new zone, and to learn how to raid as high-level should. I didn't walk away with a planes drop. I walked away with the knowledge you cannot gain from reading about a planes raid, but only from first-hand experience. I walked away from the success and pride of breaking west camp in a little over an hour, and having precious few deaths after this was done. No, I didn't do nearly as much damage as some of the higher level people, but I was welcomed as an EQUAL by everyone on that raid.<br><br><br>&gt;and (my personal favourite) it puts undue focus on items<br>&gt;which in turn often results in single-mindedness (&quot;I am<br>&gt;here because of an item, and I deserve it!&quot;)<br><br>Again I think you are taking the extreme here. You don't get a job because you don't want pay. You don't go to school because you don't want a degree. Everything you do, you do to further yourself, to gain something. Perhaps you do something to further someone else? You are still aiding your own causes by improving your &quot;standing&quot; (faction if you will) with that person. Don't misconstrue this is greed, as many seem to do.<br><br><br>That being said, I am obviously a proponent of a bonus system. However, I do realize that since CoG is not an alliance, it would be an administrative nightmare to keep up with all of it. That hardly makes it unfair though, especially considering the suggestion of &quot;paying&quot; a cleric to attend a raid.<br><br>*Throws 2cp on the ground*<br><br>(P.S. I'll start a cleric if the 10 women thing goes through <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  ) <p>Kahlus Naester<br>46 Druid<br>Officer of Legends of Valor</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhaemish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haemish</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/16/01 12:09:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=14>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.godwin.com/sd/haemish.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: FEAR RAID CONCERNS I HAVE</span><hr size=1> I work on the theory of &quot;enlightened self-interest&quot;, which is kind of a philosophy of karma within your own lifetime. If I give up something for someone one day, the universe will return the favor another day. So I run or organize raids that I might lose exp. on and not gain an item from in the hopes that other might run a raid that I will gain exp. on or an item from. Same reason I run events like the Valentine's Day dance, I run an event that is fun for others, in the hopes someone else will run an event that I can just participate in. Doesn't always work, and may take a long time to bear fruit (i.e. I could be that paladin on his 57th raid). I won't pretend that when I lead or go on a raid I don't want to get an item (Naggie has a cloak of flames with my name on it, I swear). I'd love to get something. However, the excitement of that particular raid is why I go, and the ego boost of knowing that I put X number of people to a goal, set a strategy and it works. <br><br>The concept of time of service being rewarded is an interesting one, and one I'm ambivalent about. In a guild where the players are mostly a consistent group, it would work a whole lot better, however, in an loose conglomeration like the CoG, I think there tends to be so little continuity to the whole thing that the administration is the biggest hurdle. Also, with planes and dragon type raids, the rather fluid nature of their timing (could be one day this week, then another day next week), makes continuity of raiding parties almost nonexistent. Half the people at this past Fear raid were new to me and new to the planes. There were maybe 10-15 people who had been on the previous Sacred Band plane of fear raid. After one month, the list of one time attendees could be immense. I'm just not sure that a points system would achieve the proper purpose, i.e. to get more clerics on the raid. <br><br>Haemish <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uplangstrump.showPublicProfile?language=EN>P Langstrump</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/16/01 12:37:58 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.interlog.com/~wings/jane/a_lindgren/lindgren_pics/pippi.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: FEAR RAID CONCERNS I HAVE</span><hr size=1> Kahlus, I have followed and observed a lot of alliances, and what I have said is my opinion and from what my experiences and discussion are.  Please keep that in mind.  I am not saying that other ways are incorrect or wrong, but I know that I myself feel uncomfortable and unnecessarily stressed because of those methods.  Others may swear by those rules, but they are also different people with different needs and beliefs.<br><br>Keep in mind that the current CoG system is based on a class-based RANDOM system.  Who can honestly step up and claim that another looting system is fairer than a random system? If they do, then that definition of fairness is very specific and reflects a very specific viewpoint - again, I am not saying that is incorrect, but be aware that that definition of fairness is one-sided.  And because it's only one view of fairness, people will always argue about a system that has been created by a set of people - unless they are made quiet.  And that's what I have a problem with mostly, people being self-righteous about &quot;their&quot; system being better than others and acting accordingly. It is always somewhat biased to create a reward system that is based on one factor ONLY, no matter which system it is.<br><br>And yes, since this is not an alliance, we don't keep track of attendance... who are we to judge that a person who has attended 10 CoG raids is more deserving than another person who has attended 0 CoG raids, but 10 plane raids with another guild?  <br><br>&quot;Again I think you are taking the extreme here. You don't get a job because you don't want pay. You don't go to school because you don't want a degree. Everything you do, you do to further yourself, to gain something. Perhaps you do something to further someone else? You are still aiding your own causes by improving your &quot;standing&quot; (faction if you will) with that person. Don't misconstrue this is greed, as many seem to do.&quot;<br><br>I can only agree with you here.  People should be going BECAUSE they want to go and get something out of it.  For the CoG, I have always seen that as having fun and enjoying the game, not because of an item.  But by promising that they have a greater chance at gaining an item if they go more often, the focus is directed toward gaining an item, not gaining other things.  Unfortunately, this is what this game is mostly about, and especially with the planes... it is really just a game, noone has to go to the planes. <br><br>If you don't believe me that most activities on this server are item-focused, look around and see how many alliances organize non-item-getting events.  Ask your alliance to see how many events like the dance or the chess event or the walk through antonica have been organized by them.  <br><br>A lot of people on this server participate in events to get &quot;paid&quot; or because of fixed loyalties to a specific set of people, and I will always try to discourage that in whatever I do, just because I gain satisfaction out of that <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->        <br><br>pip<br><br>p.s. scary, haemish, I have the same view about karma... you give something with no strings attached, and it will always be returned in some way or another, and in the way you least expect it. <p><HR><font size=2>Celtic: "Knowing [or Finding] the Oak Tree").... They seem to have frequented oak forests and acted as priests, teachers, and judges. (Encyclopedia Britannica)</font></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uplangstrump.showPublicProfile?language=EN>P Langstrump</A> at: 2/16/01 3:50:32 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umochaboy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MochaBoy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/16/01 1:36:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://64.37.109.125/everquest/sig2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: FEAR RAID CONCERNS I HAVE</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr>   If he fought and bled 57 times, and a random pally shows up to his 1 and only fear raid he ever plans on attending and wins a pally item, that isn't at all fair to the blood the older pally has shed not just in the name of the CoG, but in the name of EVERYONE else who has EVER won anything on a CoG raid that pally attended. Does he deserve it more than other people? Maybe. Does he deserve it more than the new pally? Yes, yes he does. And any of you who have won a roll on your own item while the older pally was there should be cheering for him to win something as well; anything else is not only unjust, it's selfish.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Khalus, this is a great point, and in that moment of decision, if I were that bloodied older paladin yes I'd feel cheated, I'd feel I deserved that item more by virtue of my sheer effort but in the end, I was denied that by my own bad luck.  And regardless of how much I've bled, regardless of how much I've fought, I'd be powerless to do anything about it.<br><br>The very nature of the KCoG is to give people the opportunity to experience things they might not be able to do on their own.  To be more specific - the KCoG allows small guilds shots at big guild opportunities.  Nowhere has it been mentioned that the KCoG is called upon to dictate who deserves what.  That's what big guilds are for.  That's what alliances are for.  If you want a better shot at getting an uber item, then the answer is to join an uber guild or an alliance that will provide you with that opportunity.  But you can't expect the KCoG which is not a governing body - just a focal point of everyone's efforts - to be called upon to determine who deserves what.<br><br>With that said however, I do believe there IS merit in the point system, but not with the way the KCoG is setup.  At it's most basic level, the KCoG is the ultimate pick up group and you all know how pickup groups go.  Because of that, there is no practical way we could implement a points based system.  I imagined it for a while a bit ago, and I thought to myself how this would drive me to drink:<br><br>/tell Kahlus ok you roll 130 1000<br>/tell Haemish ok you roll 160 1000<br>/tell Pippi ok you roll 190 1000<br>/tell Flarren you roll 550 1000<br>Fazlazen tells you, &quot;Dude what's my roll?&quot;<br>/tell Fazlazen haven't gotten to you yet<br>/tell Tanniss ok you roll 400 1000<br>Tanniss tells you &quot;wtf my roll should be 440&quot;<br>/tell Tanniss take it up with the attendance coordinator, he/she gave me these numbers<br>&lt;now we can't roll until this is resolved&gt;<br>Flarren sighs<br>Pippi munches on some Bixie crunchies while twisting her hair<br>Tanniss taps his foot impatiently<br>Somerandom dude asks if he can inspect you<br>SomeuberCleric tells you Did Ragefire pop?<br>Tanniss tells you &quot;he/she booted on zone and isn't back yet&quot;<br>/e begins to tremble nervously<br>SomeDude shouts &quot;When are we rolling&quot;<br>SomeDude shouts &quot;What's my roll range?&quot;<br>/tell Belce ok you roll 1 100<br>Belce tells you WTF, I'm a big barbarian, I'll slam your paladin ass all the way to the Nox Lair<br>/tell Belce ok 2 100<br>Belce tells you Oki!<br>Haemish tells you &quot;190 1000 right?&quot;<br>/tell Haemish wait a sec let me check<br>Lagdalen tells you never mind the bodies poofed<br><br>/q<br><br><br>Ok - a little of a dramatization - but I'd imagine it would go something like that.<br><br><br>I like our system.  <br><br>Simple is better.  <br><br>Losing 57 times in a row sucks, but hey that's life.<br><br>I agree with the spirit of what you're saying, but it can't be implemented from a practical standpoint plus I agree with Pippi that it places far too much emphasis on items rather than opportunity.  No, it's not perfect, but tampering with it and making it more complex will distract people from what the KCoG is trying to accomplish - plus there's a loophole to everything.  <br><br>So IMO, less = more.<br><br>But let me offer my own criticisms.  I suspect a 52 paladin that survived the fight because he had the requisite levels and resists would have a BIG problem losing a dragon book to a 40 paladin that died 13 seconds into the fight.  <br><br>I have a suggestion for this, give 50+ players a bonus on rolling for the books.  Level 50 rolls 1 600, level 51 rolls 1 700, level 52 rolls 1 1000, below level 50 rolls 1 500.  Or something to that effect.  This places faith in the Randomness of the roll, but still gives a bonus to those paladins who in my eyes truly do deserve the book more than the player 12 levels below them.<br><br>On the issue of effectiveness, I'm wondering if we need to raise the level limit on melees all around.  I honestly question the effectiveness of lvl 40-45 players (myself included - I only did 483 pts of damage to Vox and went back for heals 3x, but I did offer an LoH and last second battle heals).  Perhaps raising the level limit for melees to match that of casters might be in order.<br><br>What I'm trying to say is that someone level 40 was getting damaged far too quickly from clawings and AoE's to the point where they were recieving heals that should have gone to the level 50 warrior that was doing 60% more damage and lasting far longer.  <br><br><br>So I know I've rambled a bit, but just speakig what was on my mind.<br><br> <p><center><img src=http://64.37.109.125/everquest/sig.jpg></center></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/umochaboy.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MochaBoy</A> at: 2/16/01 1:43:30 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhaemish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haemish</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(2/16/01 4:11:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildscogplanesraidschedule.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=102.topic&index=17>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.godwin.com/sd/haemish.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: FEAR RAID CONCERNS I HAVE</span><hr size=1> Again, I'm not in favor of any type of system where loot is also based on level. It goes back to that thing of attaching an intrinsic value to someone's assistance. I'm a level 40, who's played for almost 2 years (with something like 44 days played, etc.) I know there are people with like 30 days played who are over level 50, due to lots more time, powerleveling, less deaths, less running around, for whatever reason. For planes, I can't even get in there for another 6-7 levels, though I'd go now if I could. So someone who's put less time into the game, and has had more opportunity to get to the planes than I is preferred over me? What is he just ebayed that character? <br><br>Here's why I always oppose preferential lottos. Where do you draw that oh so subtle thin blue line? Should guild leaders or the management body get preference? They often have to put more work into a raid than someone who just showed up. What about the level 56 guy who went LD right at the beginning of the fight in which his armour dropped? He fought for all of 2 seconds, but his level is higher, so he'd get preference. What about guilds who bring more people to the raid than other guilds? <br><br>There's a million ways you can split hairs on this issue, and a million scenarios you can show that could be considered fair, or completely unfair. In a single guild, or an alliance with fewer members, you can make a preferntial system that will be a little bit more fair but again, that's in a system where the definition of fair is more than likely fairly standard among all members. <br><br>Shoji makes a good point, that the CoG is like the ultimate pickup group, the difference being that we can do the large targets that bigger guilds can do. <br><br>I think, and have stated in the loot rules I use, that I don't think that ANY looting system will ever be 100% fair, so long as someone will get something while somoene else won't. Somebody is always going to feel like they got screwed, and the number of screwed feelings will go up as the number of people involved in the raid go up. I think that with the you bleed you roll system I use, yes, someone might get screwed, but I think that they won't feel that they were &quot;maliciously screwed&quot; by an unfair system or loot coordinator, but by random fate or chance. <br><br>I will say that I think anyone that wants to run a CoG plane raid (or any other type) is free to use whatever loot system they would like to, so long as the basic premise of fairness is maintained. I.e. if you are using a preferential system, announce it before hand, if you're trying to get X guildmate X item, tell people beforehand that that item is for him. That tends to get people really pissed off if you don't, as they then feel really screwed if they didn't know beforehand. <br><br>Haemish <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uminlain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Minlain</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http: